wiki.text:
'Ng' (pronounced ; in Eng. or ) is a Cantonese and Hakka transliteration of
the Chinese surnames / (Pinyin transliteration for Mandarin equivalent: Wú)
and (Mand. Wǔ) meaning "five". In Hokkien (Taiwanese) and Teochew, Ng
corresponds to the surname (Mand. [[Huang (surname)|Huáng]]) meaning "yellow";
or to (Mand. Ruan).

The surname is sometimes romanized as Ang, Eng, Ing and Ong in the United States
and Ung in Australia. Ng is sometimes romanized as [[Woo]] or [[Wu
(surname)|Wu]] even by people of Cantonese origin, such as John Woo. In Vietnam,
the corresponding surname is Ngô.

'吴' / 吳 (Wú) was the 10th most common Chinese surname in 2006 and was the 8th
most common in 1990.
